"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64302","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-03","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The table shows the breakdown of consumption and expenditure relating to gas and electricity for each month since June 2010. Figures are not yet available for the first quarter of Financial Year 2014-15</p><p> </p><p>The expenditure data represents physical payments in addition to the accrued expenditure posted to the Ministry of Defence accounts each month.</p><p> </p><p>Expenditure also includes standing charges as well as costs of pure consumption.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-03T14:17:39.257",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64302/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64302/answer","PQ02859 Tables.doc","Table breakdown of consumption and expenditure","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64302/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-26","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of his Department's consumption in kWh of (a) gas and (b) electricity in each month since June 2010; and what the cost of such consumption has been in each such month.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","202702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64303","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-03","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-03T13:58:05.7545062Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64303/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64303/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-26","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will publish the titles of all reports covering the effects of the use of a UK nuclear weapon produced by (a) his Department and (b) the Atomic Weapons Establishment and its predecessor body for his Department in the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","202696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64304","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-03","<p> </p><p>Two Russian Federation Navy ships transited the English Channel on 25 June 2014. These were the Ropucha Class Landing Ships Olengorsky Gornyak and Georgiy Pobedonosets.<br><br>As the hon. Member will be aware from my letter to him of 27 January 2014 (Official Report, columns 414-415W), there are usually a number of Royal Navy units available in UK waters at any one time and, if it is appropriate, one of those units could be reprioritised to undertake a required task. In this case, HMS Severn was better placed to respond, and it made the most operational sense to utilise her. At the same time the Fleet Ready Escort remained available at high readiness.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-03T14:04:05.2319906Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64304/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64304/answer","Hansard Extract 27 January.doc","Hansard Extract 27 January 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64304/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64304/answer/previousversion/7751","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64304/answer/previousversion/7751",,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-26","HMS Severn","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what Russian Navy ships HMS Severn intercepted in the English Channel on 25 June 2014; and whether HMS Severn was assigned to the Fleet Ready Escort role at that time.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","202834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64305","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>Universal credit will be fully rolled out in the next Parliament from 2017/18, and no pupil premium spending decisions for that period have yet been taken. For example, the per-pupil funding rates have not been decided beyond 2014/15. This means that it is not possible to estimate the potential cost of extending entitlement on the pupil premium budget.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-07-07T14:48:36.3453661Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64305/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64305/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will estimate the cost to the public purse of extending entitlement to benefits from the pupil premium to all claimants of universal credit once universal credit has been fully rolled out.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","202675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64306","Department for Education","false","2014-07-03","<p>Government-funded early education for three- and four-year-olds is already a universal entitlement, so there would be no cost of extending the entitlement. Universal Credit will be fully rolled out in the next Parliament, and spending decisions for that period have not been taken. This means it is, therefore not possible to estimate the potential cost on early learning for two-year-olds.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-03T16:23:17.8095034Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64306/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64306/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will estimate the cost to the public purse of extending entitlement to free early education to all claimants of universal credit once universal credit has been fully rolled out.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","202676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64307","Department for Education","false","2014-07-01","<p>In the new national curriculum, which comes into force from September 2014, swimming and water safety remain compulsory in the programme of study for physical education (PE) at primary level. We are sending a clear message to schools that swimming and water safety are essential: no other activities are specified requirements in the PE curriculum. The programme of study for PE is available online here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-in-england-physical-education-programmes-of-study" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-in-england-physical-education-programmes-of-study</a></p><p>The Department for Education is providing over £450million of ring-fenced funding across the academic years 2013/14, 2014/15 and 2015/16 to go directly to primary schools, to be spent on the improvement of PE and sport. Headteachers are best placed to decide how the funding should be used and, using the funding, they can provide additional training and instruction in swimming and water safety (over and above the requirements of the national curriculum) if they choose.</p><p>There are a range of resources to help schools provide high-quality teaching, including from organisations such as the Amateur Swimming Association and from the Royal Lifesaving Society.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-01T16:26:55.5270534Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64307/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64307/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-26","Schools: Swimming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department takes to promote the teaching of water safety in schools.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","202697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/64308","Department for Education","false","2014-07-03","<p> </p><p>The Department for Education has cut its annual energy bill by £1.4m since 2009-10 through reduced energy consumption, and has reduced its greenhouse gas emissions by 38% in the same period.</p><p>Emission reductions from energy use have largely been achieved through low and no cost energy efficiency measures, estate rationalisation (by using space more efficiently and co-locating with other organisations), and by operating our remaining buildings even more efficiently.</p><p>The Department's monthly gas and electricity consumption and associated costs since June 2010 are set out below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Electricity kWh </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Electricity Cost £</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Gas kWh </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Gas Cost £</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Jun-10</strong></p></td><td><p>1,164,652</p></td><td><p>85,441</p></td><td><p>133,998</p></td><td><p>£8,879</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Jul-10</strong></p></td><td><p>1,158,378</p></td><td><p>129,719</p></td><td><p>64,158</p></td><td><p>£9,054</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Aug-10</strong></p></td><td><p>1,019,308</p></td><td><p>120,186</p></td><td><p>17,736</p></td><td><p>£9,137</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Sep-10</strong></p></td><td><p>1,009,662</p></td><td><p>25,431</p></td><td><p>61,799</p></td><td><p>£1,789</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Oct-10</strong></p></td><td><p>972,048</p></td><td><p>81,233</p></td><td><p>168,543</p></td><td><p><strong> *</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Nov-10</strong></p></td><td><p>955,120</p></td><td><p>73,194</p></td><td><p>341,850</p></td><td><p>£3,150</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Dec-10</strong></p></td><td><p>917,993</p></td><td><p>72,450</p></td><td><p>1,368,357</p></td><td><p>£1,318</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Jan-11</strong></p></td><td><p>924,050</p></td><td><p>68,914</p></t